\h ESTHER
\toc1 Esther
\toc2 Esther
\toc3 Esth
\mt Esther
\c 1
\s The King Throws a Lavish Party
\p 
\v 1
\f + \fr 1:1 \fn 1\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft In the English Bible Esther appears adjacent to Ezra-Nehemiah and with the historical books, but in the Hebrew Bible it is one of five short books (the so-called Megillot) that appear toward the end of the biblical writings. The canonicity of the book was questioned by some in ancient Judaism and early Christianity. It is one of five OT books that were at one time regarded as \it antilegomena\it* (i.e., books “spoken against”). The problem with Esther was the absence of any direct mention of God. Some questioned whether a book that did not mention God could be considered sacred scripture. Attempts to resolve this by discovering the tetragrammaton (YHWH) encoded in the Hebrew text (e.g., in the initial letters of four consecutive words in the Hebrew text of \fx Es 5:4\fx*) are unconvincing, although they do illustrate how keenly the problem was felt by some. Martin Luther also questioned the canonicity of this book, objecting to certain parts of its content. Although no copy of Esther was found among the Dead Sea Scrolls, this does not necessarily mean that the Qumran community did not regard it as canonical. It is possible that the absence of Esther from what has survived at Qumran is merely a coincidence. Although the book does not directly mention God, it would be difficult to read it without sensing the providence of God working in powerful, though at times subtle, ways to rescue his people from danger and possible extermination. The absence of mention of the name of God may be a deliberate part of the literary strategy of the writer.\f* The following events happened 
\f + \fr 1:1 \fn 2\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “it came about”; \ver KJV\ver*, \ver ASV\ver* “Now it came to pass.”\f* in the days of Ahasuerus. 
\f + \fr 1:1 \fn 3\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft Where the Hebrew text has “Ahasuerus” (so \ver KJV\ver*, \ver NAB\ver*, \ver NASB\ver*, \ver NRSV\ver*) in this book the \ver LXX\ver* has “Artaxerxes.” The ruler mentioned in the Hebrew text is Xerxes I (ca. 486-465 \sc B.C.\sc*), and a number of modern English versions use “Xerxes” (e.g., \ver NIV\ver*, \ver NCV\ver*, \ver CEV\ver*, \ver NLT\ver*). \f* (I am referring to 
\f + \fr 1:1 \fn 4\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “in the days of Ahasuerus, that Ahasuerus who used to rule…” The phrase “I am referring to” has been supplied to clarify the force of the third person masculine singular pronoun, which is functioning like a demonstrative pronoun.\f* that Ahasuerus who used to rule over a hundred and twenty-seven provinces 
\f + \fr 1:1 \fn 5\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft The geographical extent of the Persian empire was vast. The division of Xerxes' empire into 127 smaller provinces was apparently done for purposes of administrative efficiency.\f* extending all the way from India to Ethiopia. 
\f + \fr 1:1 \fn 6\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “Cush” (so \ver NIV\ver*, \ver NCV\ver*; \ver KJV\ver* “Ethiopia”) referring to the region of the upper Nile in Africa. India and Cush (i.e., Ethiopia) are both mentioned in a tablet taken from the foundation of Xerxes' palace in Persepolis that describes the extent of this empire. See \bk ANET\bk* 316-17.\f*
) 
\v 2 In those days, as King Ahasuerus sat on his royal throne in Susa 
\f + \fr 1:2 \fn 7\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “Shushan” (so \ver KJV\ver*, \ver ASV\ver*). Most recent English versions render this as “Susa.”\fp \fl Study Note \fl* The city of \it Susa\it* served as one of several capitals of Persia during this time; the other locations were Ecbatana, Babylon, and Persepolis. Partly due to the extreme heat of its summers, Susa was a place where Persian kings stayed mainly in the winter months. Strabo indicates that reptiles attempting to cross roads at midday died from the extreme heat (\it Geography\it* 15.3.10-11).\f* the citadel, 
\f + \fr 1:2 \fn 8\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft The Hebrew word \heb בִּירָה\heb* (\theb birah\theb*) can refer to a castle or palace or temple. Here it seems to have in mind that fortified part of the city that might be called an acropolis or citadel. Cf. \ver KJV\ver* “palace”; \ver NAB\ver* “stronghold”; \ver NASB\ver* “capital”; \ver NLT\ver* “fortress.”\f* 
\v 3 in the third 
\f + \fr 1:3 \fn 9\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft The third year of Xerxes' reign would be ca. 483 \sc B.C.\sc*\f* year of his reign he provided a banquet for all his officials and his servants. The army 
\f + \fr 1:3 \fn 10\fn* \fl Textual Criticism\fl* \ft Due to the large numbers of people implied, some scholars suggest that the original text may have read “leaders of the army” (cf. \ver NAB\ver* “Persian and Median aristocracy”; \ver NASB\ver* “the army officers”; \ver NIV\ver* “the military leaders”). However, there is no textual evidence for this emendation, and the large numbers are not necessarily improbable.\f* of Persia and Media 
\f + \fr 1:3 \fn 11\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft Unlike the Book of Daniel, the usual order for this expression in Esther is “Persia and Media” (cf. vv. 14, 18, 19). In Daniel the order is “Media and Persia,” indicating a time in their history when Media was in the ascendancy.\f* was present, 
\f + \fr 1:3 \fn 12\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft The size of the banquet described here, the number of its invited guests, and the length of its duration, although certainly immense by any standard, are not without precedent in the ancient world. C. A. Moore documents a Persian banquet for 15,000 people and an Assyrian celebration with 69,574 guests (\it Esther\it* [\ver AB\ver*], 6).\f* as well as the nobles and the officials of the provinces. 
\p 
\v 4 He displayed the riches of his royal glory and the splendor of his majestic greatness for a lengthy period of time 
\f + \fr 1:4 \fn 13\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “many days” (so \ver KJV\ver*, \ver ASV\ver*); \ver NASB\ver*, \ver NRSV\ver* “for many days.”\f* – a hundred and eighty days, to be exact! 
\f + \fr 1:4 \fn 14\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft The words “to be exact!” are not in the Hebrew text but have been supplied in the translation to bring out the clarifying nuance of the time period mentioned. Cf. \ver KJV\ver* “even an hundred and fourscore days.”\f* 
\v 5 When those days 
\f + \fr 1:5 \fn 15\fn* \fl Textual Criticism\fl* \ft The Hebrew text of Esther does not indicate why this elaborate show of wealth and power was undertaken. According to the \ver LXX\ver* these were “the days of the wedding” (\grk αἱ ἡμέραι τοῦ γάμου\grk*, \tgrk hai hēmerai tou gamou\tgrk*), presumably the king's wedding. However, a number of scholars have called attention to the fact that this celebration takes place just shortly before Xerxes' invasion of Greece. It is possible that the banquet was a rallying for the up-coming military effort. See Herodotus, \it Histories\it* 7.8. There is no reason to adopt the longer reading of the \ver LXX\ver* here.\f* were completed, the king then provided a seven-day 
\f + \fr 1:5 \fn 16\fn* \fl Textual Criticism\fl* \ft The \ver LXX\ver* has \grk ἕξ\grk* (\tgrk hex\tgrk*, “six”) instead of “seven.” Virtually all English versions follow the reading of the \ver MT\ver* here, “seven.”\f* banquet for all the people who were present 
\f + \fr 1:5 \fn 17\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “were found.”\f* in Susa the citadel, for those of highest standing to the most lowly. 
\f + \fr 1:5 \fn 18\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “from the great and unto the small.”\f* It was held in the court located in the garden of the royal palace. 
\v 6 The furnishings included linen and purple curtains hung by cords of the finest linen 
\f + \fr 1:6 \fn 19\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft The\it finest linen\it* was byssus, a fine, costly, white fabric made in Egypt, Palestine, and Edom, and imported into Persia (\ver BDB\ver* 101 s.v. \heb בּוּץ\heb*; \bk HALOT\bk* 115-16 s.v. \heb בּוּץ\heb*).\f* and purple wool on silver rings, alabaster columns, gold and silver couches 
\f + \fr 1:6 \fn 20\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft The Hebrew noun \heb מִטָּה\heb* (\it mittah\it*) refers to a reclining couch (cf. \ver KJV\ver* “beds”) spread with covers, cloth and pillow for feasting and carousing (\fx Eze 23:41\fx*; \fx Am 3:12\fx*; \fx Am 6:4\fx*; \fx Es 1:6\fx*; \fx Es 7:8\fx*). See \ver BDB\ver* 641-42 s.v.; \bk HALOT\bk* 573 s.v.\f* displayed on a floor made of valuable stones of alabaster, mother-of-pearl, and mineral stone. 
\v 7 Drinks 
\f + \fr 1:7 \fn 21\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “to cause to drink” (Hiphil infinitive construct of \heb שָׁקָה\heb*, \it shaqah\it*). As the etymology of the Hebrew word for “banquet” (\heb מִשְׁתֶּה\heb*, \it mishteh\it*, from \heb שָׁתָה\heb*, \it shatah\it*, “to drink”) hints, drinking was a prominent feature of ancient Near Eastern banquets.\f* were served in golden containers, all of which differed from one another. Royal wine was available in abundance at the king's expense. 
\v 8 There were no restrictions on the drinking, 
\f + \fr 1:8 \fn 22\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “the drinking was according to law; there was no one compelling.”\f* for the king had instructed all of his supervisors 
\f + \fr 1:8 \fn 23\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “every chief of his house”; \ver KJV\ver* “all the officers of his house”; \ver NLT\ver* “his staff.”\f* that they should do as everyone so desired. 
\f + \fr 1:8 \fn 24\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “according to the desire of man and man.”\f* 
\v 9 Queen Vashti 
\f + \fr 1:9 \fn 25\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft \it Vashti\it* is the name of Xerxes' queen according to the Book of Esther. But in the Greek histories of this period the queen's name is given as Amestris (e.g., Herodotus, \it Histories\it* 9.108-13). The name Vashti does not seem to occur in the nonbiblical records from this period. Apparently the two women are not to be confused, but not enough is known about this period to reconcile completely the biblical and extrabiblical accounts.\f* also gave a banquet for the women in King Ahasuerus' royal palace. 
\s Queen Vashti is Removed from Her Royal Position
\p 
\v 10 On the seventh day, as King Ahasuerus was feeling the effects of the wine, 
\f + \fr 1:10 \fn 26\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “as the heart of the king was good with the wine.” Here the proper name (King Ahasuerus) has been substituted for the title in the translation for stylistic reasons.\f* he ordered Mehuman, Biztha, Harbona, Bigtha, Abagtha, Zethar, and Carcas, the seven eunuchs who attended him, 
\f + \fr 1:10 \fn 27\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “King Ahasuerus”; here the proper name has been replaced by the pronoun “him” in the translation for stylistic reasons. Cf. similarly \ver NIV\ver*, \ver NCV\ver*, \ver CEV\ver*, \ver NLT\ver* “King Xerxes.”\f* 
\v 11 to bring Queen Vashti into the king's presence wearing her royal high turban. He wanted to show the people and the officials her beauty, for she was very attractive. 
\f + \fr 1:11 \fn 28\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “was good of appearance”; \ver KJV\ver* “was fair to look on”; \ver NAB\ver* “was lovely to behold.”\f* 
\v 12 But Queen Vashti refused 
\f + \fr 1:12 \fn 29\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft Refusal to obey the king was risky even for a queen in the ancient world. It is not clear why Vashti behaved so rashly and put herself in such danger. Apparently she anticipated humiliation of some kind and was unwilling to subject herself to it, in spite of the obvious dangers. There is no justification in the biblical text for an ancient Jewish targumic tradition that the king told her to appear before his guests dressed in \it nothing but\it* her royal high turban, that is, essentially naked.\f* to come at the king's bidding 
\f + \fr 1:12 \fn 30\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “at the word of the king”; \ver NASB\ver* “at the king's command.”\f* conveyed through the eunuchs. Then the king became extremely angry, and his rage consumed 
\f + \fr 1:12 \fn 31\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “burned in him” (so \ver KJV\ver*).\f* him. 
\p 
\v 13 The king then inquired of the wise men who were discerners of the times – for it was the royal custom to confer with all those who were proficient in laws and legalities. 
\f + \fr 1:13 \fn 32\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “judgment” (so \ver KJV\ver*); \ver NASB\ver*, \ver NIV\ver* “justice”; \ver NRSV\ver* “custom.”\f* 
\v 14 Those who were closest to him were Carshena, Shethar, Admatha, Tarshish, Meres, Marsena, and Memucan. These men were the seven officials of Persia and Media who saw the king on a regular basis 
\f + \fr 1:14 \fn 33\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “seers of the face of the king”; \ver NASB\ver* “who had access to the king's presence.”\f* and had the most prominent offices 
\f + \fr 1:14 \fn 34\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “were sitting first”; \ver NAB\ver* “held first rank in the realm.”\f* in the kingdom. 
\v 15 The king asked, 
\f + \fr 1:15 \fn 35\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft These words are not present in the Hebrew text, but have been supplied in the translation for clarity (cf. \ver NIV\ver*, \ver NCV\ver*, \ver CEV\ver*, \ver NLT\ver*, all of which supply similar phrases).\f* “By law, 
\f + \fr 1:15 \fn 36\fn* \fl Textual Criticism\fl* \ft The location of the prepositional phrase “according to law” is somewhat unusual in the Hebrew text, but not so much so as to require emendation. Some scholars suggest deleting the phrase as an instance of dittography from the final part of the immediately preceding word in v. 14. Others suggest taking the phrase with the end of v. 14 rather than with v. 15. Both proposals, however, lack adequate justification.\f* what should be done to Queen Vashti in light of the fact that she has not obeyed the instructions of King Ahasuerus conveyed through the eunuchs?” 
\p 
\v 16 Memucan then replied to the king and the officials, “The wrong of Queen Vashti is not against the king alone, but against all the officials and all the people who are throughout all the provinces of King Ahasuerus. 
\v 17 For the matter concerning the queen will spread to all the women, leading them to treat their husbands with contempt, saying, ‘When King Ahasuerus gave orders to bring Queen Vashti into his presence, she would not come.’ 
\v 18 And this very day the noble ladies of Persia and Media who have heard the matter concerning the queen will respond in the same way to all the royal officials, and there will be more than enough contempt and anger! 
\v 19 If the king is so inclined, 
\f + \fr 1:19 \fn 37\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “If upon the king it is good”; \ver KJV\ver* “If it please the king.” Deferential language was common in ancient Near Eastern court language addressing a despot; it occurs often in Esther.\f* let a royal edict go forth from him, and let it be written in the laws of Persia and Media that cannot be repealed, 
\f + \fr 1:19 \fn 38\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft \it Laws…that cannot be repealed\it*. On the permanence of the laws of Media and Persia see also \fx Es 8:8\fx* and \fx Da 6:8\fx*, \fx Da 6:12\fx*, \fx Da 6:15\fx*.\f* that Vashti 
\f + \fr 1:19 \fn 39\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft Previously in this chapter the word “queen” accompanies Vashti's name (cf. vv. 9, 11, 12, 15, 16, 17). But here, in anticipation of her demotion, the title is dropped.\f* may not come into the presence of King Ahasuerus, and let the king convey her royalty to another 
\f + \fr 1:19 \fn 40\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “her neighbor”; \ver NIV\ver* “someone else.”\f* who is more deserving than she. 
\f + \fr 1:19 \fn 41\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “who is better than she.” The reference is apparently to worthiness of the royal position as demonstrated by compliance with the king's wishes, although the word \heb טוֹב\heb* (\theb tob\theb*, “good”) can also be used of physical beauty. Cf. \ver NAB\ver*, \ver NASB\ver*, \ver NLT\ver* “more worthy than she.”\f* 
\v 20 And let the king's decision which he will enact be disseminated 
\f + \fr 1:20 \fn 42\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “heard”; \ver KJV\ver*, \ver NAB\ver*, \ver NLT\ver* “published”; \ver NIV\ver*, \ver NRSV\ver* “proclaimed.”\f* throughout all his kingdom, vast though it is. 
\f + \fr 1:20 \fn 43\fn* \fl Textual Criticism\fl* \ft The phrase “vast though it is” is not included in the \ver LXX\ver*, although it is retained by almost all English versions.\f* Then all the women will give honor to their husbands, from the most prominent to the lowly.” 
\p 
\v 21 The matter seemed appropriate to the king and the officials. So the king acted on the advice of Memucan. 
\v 22 He sent letters throughout all the royal provinces, to each province according to its own script and to each people according to its own language, 
\f + \fr 1:22 \fn 44\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft For purposes of diplomacy and governmental communication throughout the far-flung regions of the Persian empire the Aramaic language was normally used. Educated people throughout the kingdom could be expected to have competence in this language. But in the situation described in v. 22 a variety of local languages are to be used, and not just Aramaic, so as to make the king's edict understandable to the largest possible number of people.\f* that every man should be ruling his family 
\f + \fr 1:22 \fn 45\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “in his house”; \ver NIV\ver* “over his own household.”\f* and should be speaking the language of his own people. 
\f + \fr 1:22 \fn 46\fn* \fl Textual Criticism\fl* \ft The final prepositional phrase is not included in the \ver LXX\ver*, and this shorter reading is followed by a number of English versions (e.g., \ver NAB\ver*, \ver NRSV\ver*, \ver NLT\ver*). Some scholars suggest the phrase may be the result of dittography from the earlier phrase “to each people according to its language,” but this is not a necessary conclusion. The edict was apparently intended to reassert male prerogative with regard to two things (and not just one): sovereign and unquestioned leadership within the family unit, and the right of deciding which language was to be used in the home when a bilingual situation existed.\f*
\c 2
\s Esther Becomes Queen in Vashti's Place
\p 
\v 1 When these things had been accomplished 
\f + \fr 2:1 \fn 1\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “after these things” (so \ver KJV\ver*, \ver NASB\ver*, \ver NRSV\ver*). The expression is very vague from a temporal standpoint, not indicating precisely just how much time might have elapsed. Cf. v. 21.\f* and the rage of King Ahasuerus had diminished, he remembered 
\f + \fr 2:1 \fn 2\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft There may be a tinge of regret expressed in the king's remembrance of Vashti. There is perhaps a hint that he wished for her presence once again, although that was not feasible from a practical standpoint. The suggestions by the king's attendants concerning a replacement seem to be an effort to overcome this nostalgia. Certainly it was to their advantage to seek the betterment of the king's outlook. Those around him the most were probably the most likely to suffer the effects of his ire.\f* Vashti and what she had done and what had been decided 
\f + \fr 2:1 \fn 3\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft Or “decreed” (so \ver NAB\ver*, \ver NASB\ver*, \ver NRSV\ver*); \ver TEV\ver* “and about his proclamation against her.”\f* against her. 
\v 2 The king's servants who attended him said, “Let a search be conducted in the king's behalf for attractive young women. 
\f + \fr 2:2 \fn 4\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “young women, virgins, good of form.” The same phrase also occurs in v. 3.\f* 
\v 3 And let the king appoint officers throughout all the provinces of his kingdom to gather all the attractive young women to Susa the citadel, to the harem 
\f + \fr 2:3 \fn 5\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “the house of the women” (so \ver KJV\ver*, \ver ASV\ver*). So also in vv. 9, 11, 13, and \fx Es 2:14\fx*.\f* under the authority of Hegai, the king's eunuch who oversees the women, and let him provide whatever cosmetics they desire. 
\f + \fr 2:3 \fn 6\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “their ointments”; cf. \ver NIV\ver*, \ver CEV\ver*, \ver NLT\ver* “beauty treatments.”\f* 
\v 4 Let the young woman whom the king finds most attractive 
\f + \fr 2:4 \fn 7\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “who is good in the eyes of the king.”\f* become queen in place of Vashti.” This seemed like a good idea to the king, 
\f + \fr 2:4 \fn 8\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “the matter was good in the eyes of the king.” Cf. \ver TEV\ver* “The king thought this was good advice.”\f* so he acted accordingly. 
\p 
\v 5 Now there happened to be a Jewish man in Susa the citadel whose name was Mordecai. 
\f + \fr 2:5 \fn 9\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft \it Mordecai\it* is a pagan name that reflects the name of the Babylonian deity Marduk. Probably many Jews of the period had two names, one for secular use and the other for use especially within the Jewish community. Mordecai's Jewish name is not recorded in the biblical text.\f* He was the son of Jair, the son of Shimei, the son of Kish, a Benjaminite, 
\v 6 who had been taken into exile from Jerusalem 
\f + \fr 2:6 \fn 10\fn* \fl Map\fl* \ft For location see \jmp MAP5-B1|fig:Map5.jpg\jmp*; \jmp MAP6-F3|fig:Map6.jpg\jmp*; \jmp MAP7-E2|fig:Map7.jpg\jmp*; \jmp MAP8-F2|fig:Map8.jpg\jmp*; \jmp MAP10-B3|fig:Map10.jpg\jmp*; \jmp JP1-F4|fig:JP1.jpg\jmp*; \jmp JP2-F4|fig:JP2.jpg\jmp*; \jmp JP3-F4|fig:JP3.jpg\jmp*; \jmp JP4-F4|fig:JP4.jpg\jmp*.\f* with the captives who had been carried into exile with Jeconiah 
\f + \fr 2:6 \fn 11\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft \it Jeconiah\it* is an alternative name for Jehoiachin. A number of modern English versions use the latter name to avoid confusion (e.g., \ver NIV\ver*, \ver NCV\ver*, \ver TEV\ver*, \ver NLT\ver*).\f* king of Judah, whom Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon had taken into exile. 
\v 7 Now he was acting as the guardian 
\f + \fr 2:7 \fn 12\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft According to \bk HALOT\bk* 64 s.v. II \heb אמן\heb* the term \heb אֹמֵן\heb* (\theb ’omen\theb*) means: (1) “attendant” of children (\fx Nu 11:12\fx*; \fx Is 49:23\fx*); (2) “guardian” (\fx 2Ki 10:1\fx*, \fx 2Ki 10:5\fx*; \fx Es 2:7\fx*); (3) “nurse-maid” (\fx 2Sa 4:4\fx*; \fx Ru 4:16\fx*); and (4) “to look after” (\fx Is 60:4\fx*; \fx La 4:5\fx*). Older lexicons did not distinguish this root from the homonym I \heb אָמַן\heb* (\theb ’aman\theb*, “to support; to confirm”; cf. \ver BDB\ver* 52 s.v. \heb אָמַן\heb*). This is reflected in a number of translations by use of a phrase like “brought up” (\ver KJV\ver*, \ver ASV\ver*, \ver RSV\ver*, \ver NIV\ver*) or “bringing up” (\ver NASB\ver*).\f* of Hadassah 
\f + \fr 2:7 \fn 13\fn* \fl Study Note \fl* \ft \it Hadassah\it* is a Jewish name that probably means “myrtle”; the name \it Esther\it* probably derives from the Persian word for “star,” although some scholars derive it from the name of the Babylonian goddess Ishtar. Esther is not the only biblical character for whom two different names were used. Daniel (renamed Belteshazzar) and his three friends Hananiah (renamed Shadrach), Mishael (renamed Meshach), and Azariah (renamed Abednego) were also given different names by their captors.\f* (that is, Esther), the daughter of his uncle, for neither her father nor her mother was alive. 
\f + \fr 2:7 \fn 14\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “for there was not to her father or mother.” This is universally understood to mean Esther's father and mother were no longer alive.\f* This young woman was very attractive and had a beautiful figure. 
\f + \fr 2:7 \fn 15\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “beautiful of form.” The Hebrew noun \heb תֹּאַר\heb* (\theb to’ar\theb*, “form; shape”) is used elsewhere to describe the physical bodily shape of a beautiful woman (\fx Ge 29:17\fx*; \fx De 21:11\fx*; \fx 1Sa 25:3\fx*); see \ver BDB\ver* 1061 s.v. Cf. \ver TEV\ver* “had a good figure.”\f* When her father and mother died, Mordecai had raised her 
\f + \fr 2:7 \fn 16\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “had taken her to him.” The Hebrew verb \heb לָקַח\heb* (\theb laqakh\theb*, “to take”) describes Mordecai adopting Esther and treating her like his own daughter: “to take as one's own property” as a daughter (\bk HALOT\bk* 534 s.v. I \heb לקח\heb* 6).\f* as if she were his own daughter. 
\p 
\v 8 It so happened that when the king's edict and his law became known 
\f + \fr 2:8 \fn 17\fn* \fl Translator's Note\fl* \ft \it Heb\it* “were heard” (so \ver NASB\ver*); \ver NRSV\ver* “were (had been \ver NIV\ver*) proclaimed.”\f* many young women were taken to Susa the citadel to be placed under the authority of Hegai. Esther also was taken to the royal palace 
